    "summary": "Qin Shi Huang's Wars of Unification (230–221 BC) were the final military campaigns of the [[event:1111|Warring States Period]], in which the Qin state under King Zheng (who became [[event:3141|Qin Shi Huang]]) conquered the remaining six warring states in rapid succession, creating a unified Chinese empire for the first time in history.\n\nThe conquests followed a methodical strategy: beginning with the weakest states (Han in 230 BC, Zhao in 228 BC), neutralizing potential coalitions, and saving the largest (Chu) for when Qin's military was at peak strength. The final campaigns were led by experienced generals including Wang Jian and his son Wang Ben. Each conquered state's aristocracy was relocated, its weapons confiscated, its walls demolished. Within a decade, [[event:76|Qin Dynasty / Unification of China]] had absorbed all rivals. The creation of the first unified Chinese empire — and the accompanying administrative and cultural standardization — was arguably the most consequential political event in Chinese history, establishing the model of a unified Chinese state that would persist, with interruptions, for over two millennia.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin%27s_wars_of_unification",
